	   <tr><td colspan=2>I too agree that paladins are not insane and bloodthirsty fighters.&nbsp;&nbsp;We are the thinking man's warrior.  At lower levels the difference will not seem to be much, but as you advance into the high 40's and mid 50's, you will begin to discover that you are <b>not</b> the primary tank.  Warriors do this many times better than us.<br><br>What edge do we have, though?  I see being an ideal paladin paralell to being a ballet dancer.  Weave in, attack, back off and heal the warrior when the cleric messes up complete healing timing, LH the enchanter to give your group time to escape, do a triple axel and stun the baddies into oblivion. :)<br><br>Dual wield is not an option, I wouldn't give up high damage one handers and two handers for anything.  Again, we come off as a thinking warrior, a holy man and not a fanatic.<br><br>My only gripe is the lack of disciplines at high levels, which are sorely needed for high level encounters like Venril Sathir and Lord Rak`Ashiir.  Maybe the auto-parry discipline for us?  Auto-riposte?  Defensive?  Something defensive in nature, offense is left to the <b>real</b> damage dealing tanks (i.e. those that can dual wield).<br><br>Come to think of it, you've inspired me to write up that high-level paladin guide I've been thinking about for a while.  Thanks Kilraven. :)<br>&nbsp;<br><b>Praetor</b>, 60th Crusader<br>Avatars of Discord</td></tr>
